      "content": "A \"goblin\" object is just a metaphor for a small, persistent piece of code that you can use to track memory leaks, but it's not a standard debugging pattern or a specific library. It's a term I'm using to describe a simple counter or a small object that you can create in your code to help you monitor memory usage.\n\nTo use it, you can create a simple class or struct that increments a counter every time you allocate memory and decrements it when you deallocate. This way, you can track the total number of allocations and deallocations in your program.\n\nHere's an example of how you can implement a simple \"goblin\" counter:\n\n```cpp\nclass GoblinCounter {\npublic:\n    static int getAllocationCount() { return allocationCount; }\n    static int getDeallocationCount() { return deallocationCount; }\n    static int getNetAllocationCount() { return allocationCount - deallocationCount; }\n\nprivate:\n    static int allocationCount;\n    static int deallocationCount;\n};\n\nint GoblinCounter::allocationCount = 0;\nint GoblinCounter::deallocationCount = 0;\n```\n\nYou can then wrap your `new",
